A quick tactical note: h4×g5 would drop the pawn for nothing after ...f6, so recapture is better with an immediate piece.  
More importantly, 26. Qxh7+ is already possible, but after …Kg7 Black keeps resources.  A cleaner blow is 26. Bxg5, annihilating Black’s kingside cover and setting up unavoidable threats such as Qh7+/Qg6+ with the rook coming to h1.  After Bxg5 Black will lose critical pawns or simply be mated.

First, let’s sacrifice the bishop to rip open the kingside.

[g5g5B] is illegal notation; instead

[ f1g1 ]  –moving the rook off the long diagonal so both bishops can retreat/ swing to the kingside as needed–was considered, but direct tactics are stronger.

Therefore the simplest and most forcing is simply to recapture on g5 with the bishop, then queen slides in.
